strained the utmost limits.

00:02:40.700 --> 00:02:43.910
And also, even if you
want to handle wastes,

00:02:43.910 --> 00:02:46.930
then the cost is exorbitant.

00:02:46.930 --> 00:02:51.270
So we found that in
the last 100 years,

00:02:51.270 --> 00:02:54.560
that has been a paradigm shift
from decreasing resources

00:02:54.560 --> 00:02:57.170
to increasing wastes.

00:02:57.170 --> 00:03:00.680
And as a result, we
assume that nature

00:03:00.680 --> 00:03:04.130
will subsidize the cost of
converting the wastes back

00:03:04.130 --> 00:03:06.190
into resources.

00:03:06.190 --> 00:03:09.260
So it doesn't happen
like that because only

00:03:09.260 --> 00:03:12.620
to a certain extent
nature will do that.

00:03:12.620 --> 00:03:16.220
Therefore, ecological
resilience strained to a limit

00:03:16.220 --> 00:03:20.550
is a very interesting
feature, because government

00:03:20.550 --> 00:03:23.750
is spending a tremendous
amount of money

00:03:23.750 --> 00:03:25.680
to bring things under control.

00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:28.300
When we find that
food costs are rising,

00:03:28.300 --> 00:03:30.880
air pollution is
increasing, and we

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:35.770
find that transportation
costs is increased,

00:03:35.770 --> 00:03:38.050
it becomes extremely
difficult for solid waste

00:03:38.050 --> 00:03:40.360
to be transported
and what to speak

00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:44.310
of water, which
is such a demand.

00:03:44.310 --> 00:03:46.060
And we find that water
is being utilized

00:03:46.060 --> 00:03:48.870
for more and more activities.

00:03:48.870 --> 00:03:52.830
And the next crisis is seriously
going to be that of water.

00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:55.710
So considering
that, we are trying

00:03:55.710 --> 00:03:59.380
to figure out what is the root
cause analysis of the problem.

00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:02.640
So you find that the root
cause solution, the root cause

00:04:02.640 --> 00:04:07.630
is the irreversible conversion
of resources into wastes.

00:04:07.630 --> 00:04:12.410
The concept we thought of, if we
could devise a system by which

00:04:12.410 --> 00:04:16.910
the wastes could be converted
back into resources then

00:04:16.910 --> 00:04:20.970
the problem of increasing
waste and decreasing resources

00:04:20.970 --> 00:04:25.840
could be solved, because
we'll have a sustainable loop.

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:28.410
Then, ecological
resilience strained

00:04:28.410 --> 00:04:31.720
to a limit, if the waste
becomes a resource, then

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:34.820
you a reversible system which
is very close to nature,

00:04:34.820 --> 00:04:37.820
because that's what
nature naturally does.

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:39.910
And the increasing
cost of waste handling

00:04:39.910 --> 00:04:42.530
would be irrelevant, because
your waste is actually

00:04:42.530 --> 00:04:46.210
becoming a resource.

00:04:46.210 --> 00:04:48.980
So therefore, waste--
in definition--

00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:53.800
is an object which neither in
partial or totality contributes

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:55.930
to the end goal of a system.

00:04:55.930 --> 00:04:58.570
So we have two kinds of waste--
immediate waste and delayed

00:04:58.570 --> 00:04:59.810
waste.

00:04:59.810 --> 00:05:02.110
And therefore, we were
trying to figure out

00:05:02.110 --> 00:05:06.900
a concept where the
waste could actually

00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:10.460
become the resource
for the next system.

00:05:10.460 --> 00:05:13.000
Then that second
system produces a waste

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.470
that, if it becomes a
resource for the third system,

00:05:16.470 --> 00:05:18.700
then through this
methodology, we'll

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:22.320
have something called a
symbiotic recycling, where

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:24.820
every waste is
becoming a resource.

00:05:24.820 --> 00:05:27.480
And in one sense, we
are trying to remodel

00:05:27.480 --> 00:05:30.120
what naturally
happens in nature.

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:32.840
In nature, we go
through the cycle.

00:05:32.840 --> 00:05:35.270
And the cyclical
chain takes one system

00:05:35.270 --> 00:05:38.850
to the next system in a
smooth, seamless fashion.

00:05:38.850 --> 00:05:41.660
We also find it
in the water cycle

00:05:41.660 --> 00:05:45.640
and in the nitrogen cycle, where
seamlessly, one system just

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:49.160
merges into the other system,
because the waste of one system

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:52.150
becomes a resource
for another system.

00:05:52.150 --> 00:05:55.280
So therefore, in a linear
model, what we find

00:05:55.280 --> 00:06:00.690
is that the resource being
consumed converts into waste.

00:06:00.690 --> 00:06:03.560
So this is a linear
resource-to-trash model,

00:06:03.560 --> 00:06:06.210
where at the end of
all the resources,

00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:09.130
you're left with a
whole lot of wastes.

00:06:09.130 --> 00:06:12.330
And we do not have any
clue how to deal with them.

00:06:12.330 --> 00:06:15.690
Whereas, in a system
of symbiotic recycling,

00:06:15.690 --> 00:06:18.070
instead of the resource
being converted

00:06:18.070 --> 00:06:21.600
to waste as a consumer,
the resource actually

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:26.020
converts into a waste and
waste one becomes resource two.

00:06:26.020 --> 00:06:28.570
So it actually
becomes a contributor.

00:06:28.570 --> 00:06:32.190
So we are devising a system by
which the consumer is no longer

00:06:32.190 --> 00:06:36.250
called a consumer, he will
be called a contributor.

00:06:36.250 --> 00:06:39.490
And therefore,
this is the system

00:06:39.490 --> 00:06:42.030
which we're trying to
apply in our ecovillage.

00:06:42.030 --> 00:06:45.860
And I'll share with you
the details very soon.

00:06:45.860 --> 00:06:49.240
So basically,
sustainability is defined

00:06:49.240 --> 00:06:53.550
as the interface between
bearability, viability,

00:06:53.550 --> 00:06:56.470
and equitability when
social, environment,

00:06:56.470 --> 00:06:59.520
and economic factors interface.

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:01.510
So when we are discussing
the whole concept

00:07:01.510 --> 00:07:05.130
of sustainability,
then human society,

00:07:05.130 --> 00:07:08.530
if it has to remain for
long periods of time,

00:07:08.530 --> 00:07:12.760
has to be in this
operating zone.

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:15.530
Therefore, the top 10
problems of the world

00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:19.850
is global warming, economic
collapse, peak oil and energy

00:07:19.850 --> 00:07:24.110
consumption, urbanization,
water crisis, malnutrition,

00:07:24.110 --> 00:07:26.810
nuclear proliferation,
war, terrorism,

00:07:26.810 --> 00:07:29.630
and loss of biodiversity.

00:07:29.630 --> 00:07:33.330
And at the ecovillage, we try to
integrate all of these factors

00:07:33.330 --> 00:07:34.760
together.

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:39.430
And we try to address the issue
of global warming by making

00:07:39.430 --> 00:07:43.240
green buildings and integrating
a green waste management

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:48.040
system, global economic
collapse with rural empowerment,

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:51.490
peak oil and energy consumption/
energy crisis by using

00:07:51.490 --> 00:07:54.670
alternative energy
and using animals,

00:07:54.670 --> 00:07:58.210
urbanization and population
by rural empowerment,

00:07:58.210 --> 00:08:01.900
global water crisis with our
water conservation and soil

00:08:01.900 --> 00:08:05.390
biotechnology-- which is a
green technology for sewage

00:08:05.390 --> 00:08:08.340
management, which I'll be
sharing with you right now--

00:08:08.340 --> 00:08:11.980
malnutrition and food security
issues by using organic

00:08:11.980 --> 00:08:15.210
agriculture, and loss of
biodiversity and species

00:08:15.210 --> 00:08:19.020
extinction with also
organic agriculture.

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:22.730
So basically, ours was a
community set up in 2003.

00:08:22.730 --> 00:08:25.090
You must have a lot of
place called Mumbai,

00:08:25.090 --> 00:08:29.320
and 108 kilometers away
from Mumbai on the north

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:31.980
is the Govardhan Ecovillage.

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:36.240
And the concept of GEV's based
on sustainable technologies,

00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:40.630
which are very effective
in urban, semi-urban,

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:42.510
and rural areas.

00:08:42.510 --> 00:08:46.840
As far as waste is concerned,
four types of waste

00:08:46.840 --> 00:08:49.430
are created in our property.

00:08:49.430 --> 00:08:52.350
We have animal waste
and food waste.

00:08:52.350 --> 00:08:55.730
Second is we have dry,
biodegradable waste

00:08:55.730 --> 00:08:57.210
like foliage.

00:08:57.210 --> 00:08:59.770
And then you have
non-biodegradable--

00:08:59.770 --> 00:09:02.910
that is plastics and
construction aggregate.

00:09:02.910 --> 00:09:05.890
And human waste, the black
and grey water, et cetera,

00:09:05.890 --> 00:09:08.970
which constitute the sewage.

00:09:08.970 --> 00:09:11.470
So therefore, how do
we fit in the puzzle

00:09:11.470 --> 00:09:13.990
with all of these wastes
being put together?

00:09:13.990 --> 00:09:18.580
So let's spend a few moments
on this picture, where

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:21.000
the entire concept of
symbiotic recycling

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:24.310
is explained at one glance.

00:09:24.310 --> 00:09:27.530
So you look at to figure
where there is this cow.

00:09:27.530 --> 00:09:33.690
So the cow eats on the
grass and it gives cow dung.

00:09:33.690 --> 00:09:37.670
OK, so the input for
the cow is the grass.

00:09:37.670 --> 00:09:39.720
The grass is the
fodder for the cow.

00:09:39.720 --> 00:09:43.060
The output from the
cow is the cow dung.

00:09:43.060 --> 00:09:46.970
So interestingly enough for
many of you-- who may or may not

00:09:46.970 --> 00:09:50.100
know-- one of the
best forms of manure

00:09:50.100 --> 00:09:54.070
which we have experimented
with is made with cow dung.

00:09:54.070 --> 00:09:59.730
So cow dung is one of the
top-notch fertilizers which

00:09:59.730 --> 00:10:03.180
actually creates such
a fertile ground.

00:10:03.180 --> 00:10:08.220
So if you leave the cow
and the earth alone,

00:10:08.220 --> 00:10:11.260
both will sustain each other.

00:10:11.260 --> 00:10:13.680
The earth will give grass.

00:10:13.680 --> 00:10:16.030
The cow will eat the
good, give cow dung.

00:10:16.030 --> 00:10:19.690
That cow dung will give more
grass when it hits the ground.

00:10:19.690 --> 00:10:23.000
And in this way, both take care
of each other perfectly well.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.250
It's a sustainable system.

00:10:25.250 --> 00:10:28.660
But then, you bring
in human being.

00:10:28.660 --> 00:10:32.040
So the human, he wants to live.

00:10:32.040 --> 00:10:35.450
OK, so naturally, he
cannot live under the sky.

00:10:35.450 --> 00:10:38.230
So he needs a house to live.

00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:40.860
OK, so what do we do?

00:10:40.860 --> 00:10:44.760
The human being needs three
things-- a house to live,

00:10:44.760 --> 00:10:49.180
a food to eat,
energy to sustain.

00:10:49.180 --> 00:10:52.710
So if you look at this
figure, you find a hut.

00:10:52.710 --> 00:10:56.690
That house is made
with mud blocks.

00:10:56.690 --> 00:11:01.520
So we created 250,000
blocks made out of mud,

00:11:01.520 --> 00:11:05.030
adding 8% cement, and
they're called compassed,

00:11:05.030 --> 00:11:07.040
stabilized earth blocks.

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:08.520
It's called green building.

00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:11.460
It's called green earth blocks.

00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:16.530
So when you have buildings which
are made out of earth blocks,

00:11:16.530 --> 00:11:19.560
then it's a breathing
wall and you have very low

00:11:19.560 --> 00:11:21.950
embodied energy.

00:11:21.950 --> 00:11:25.000
OK, so you have created
a dwelling place

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.650
which is as green as possible.

00:11:27.650 --> 00:11:30.710
But then, he also
needs food to eat.

00:11:30.710 --> 00:11:32.280
So how does the food come?

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:34.180
So from the cow dung,
you have other kinds

00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:36.220
of crops which can be grown.

00:11:36.220 --> 00:11:39.440
So on that card what
you see is rice.

00:11:39.440 --> 00:11:41.760
So one of the greatest
challenges in India

00:11:41.760 --> 00:11:46.080
is also to preserve the
indigenous varieties of rice.

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:51.730
So on our property, we grow 54
varieties of indigenous rice.

00:11:51.730 --> 00:11:54.160
And you'll be amazed to know
that some of those varieties

00:11:54.160 --> 00:11:56.290
are highly medicinal
in property.

00:11:56.290 --> 00:11:59.130
And simply by consuming
those varieties of rice,

00:11:59.130 --> 00:12:02.690
many of the medical
problems can be solved.

00:12:02.690 --> 00:12:06.060
So therefore, indigenous
varieties of rice--

00:12:06.060 --> 00:12:08.890
but without using harmful
chemical pesticides

00:12:08.890 --> 00:12:13.940
and fertilizers-- and with
that, the organic farming

00:12:13.940 --> 00:12:15.790
you grow this food.

00:12:15.790 --> 00:12:17.840
So the input for
that is the cow dung.

00:12:17.840 --> 00:12:19.510
The output is the food.

00:12:19.510 --> 00:12:23.270
Then, the food is eaten
by the human being.

00:12:23.270 --> 00:12:28.540
And then, what comes out-- now
you need the food to be cooked.

00:12:28.540 --> 00:12:29.570
So how do you use that?

00:12:29.570 --> 00:12:32.990
So the cow dung,
again, is used in what

00:12:32.990 --> 00:12:35.940
is known as a bio-gas plant.

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:39.660
So in a bio-gas plant,
cow dung becomes an input.

00:12:39.660 --> 00:12:43.290
And what comes out is fuel.

00:12:43.290 --> 00:12:47.530
And that fuel is
used for cooking.

00:12:47.530 --> 00:12:50.200
And that cooking
ultimately cooks

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:52.980
the food which the
humans can eat.

00:12:52.980 --> 00:12:55.760
And then, after the humans
eat that, what comes out

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:57.370
is the sewage.

00:12:57.370 --> 00:13:03.090
So you see on the right side
is this rectangular structure.

00:13:03.090 --> 00:13:06.050
That is the sewage
treatment plant,

00:13:06.050 --> 00:13:09.750
which is known as the
soil biotechnology plant.

00:13:09.750 --> 00:13:12.220
And we'll discuss
about that also.

00:13:12.220 --> 00:13:15.410
But that input for
that is the sewage.

00:13:15.410 --> 00:13:17.480
The sewage comes
out, and it goes

00:13:17.480 --> 00:13:19.680
through that sewage
technology plant.

00:13:19.680 --> 00:13:23.570
And what comes out
is fish fit water.

00:13:23.570 --> 00:13:27.840
Fish fit water means water
in which fishes can dwell.

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:31.140
But it's a completely
green sewage technology

00:13:31.140 --> 00:13:35.940
with hardly any downtime and
practically no sound at all.

00:13:35.940 --> 00:13:40.210
And it is composed of rocks in
different layers, geofigures,

00:13:40.210 --> 00:13:43.880
earthworms, and various
kinds of bio-reactors

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:49.640
which generate over 10 million
liters of sewage-- sewage water

00:13:49.640 --> 00:13:54.090
can water 10 million liters
of fresh water every year.

00:13:54.090 --> 00:13:56.880
And that output, which
is irrigatable water,

00:13:56.880 --> 00:13:58.570
goes into irrigation.

00:13:58.570 --> 00:14:02.190
That output becomes the
input for the fields.

00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:06.000
And then again, the
same chain continues.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.760
So we have in this
way created a system

00:14:09.760 --> 00:14:14.620
by which every output
is becoming an input.

00:14:14.620 --> 00:14:20.380
And thus, we are regenerating
sources of energy

00:14:20.380 --> 00:14:23.110
which we would not
have thought of before.

00:14:23.110 --> 00:14:26.170
So this is, in brief, what
we are trying to describe.

00:14:28.760 --> 00:14:32.640
So therefore, food, shelter,
and energy is required.

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:34.910
And what human being
generates is waste, sewage,

00:14:34.910 --> 00:14:38.090
construction waste,
and domestic waste.

00:14:38.090 --> 00:14:41.270
OK, so fulfilling the
human need, food is there,

00:14:41.270 --> 00:14:43.670
the grain is there, the
milk products is there.

00:14:43.670 --> 00:14:45.850
And this is the actual
pictures of what

00:14:45.850 --> 00:14:47.940
we are grown there on our plant.

00:14:47.940 --> 00:14:50.830
We have 100 varieties
of mango, also.

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:54.060
Mango is a fruit which
grows very famously

00:14:54.060 --> 00:14:56.040
in [INAUDIBLE] in that area.

00:14:56.040 --> 00:15:00.640
So we have sugar cane,
rice, [INAUDIBLE]

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:03.670
and various kinds
of organic fruits.

00:15:03.670 --> 00:15:06.280
And if you see
here, what you see

00:15:06.280 --> 00:15:10.110
in that [INAUDIBLE]
bed is earthen bricks.

00:15:10.110 --> 00:15:11.730
That is a construction
waste which

00:15:11.730 --> 00:15:14.820
is utilized for creating
permanent and raised bed

00:15:14.820 --> 00:15:16.000
system.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:17.620
So the permanent
raised bed system

00:15:17.620 --> 00:15:19.290
is a technique by
which you increase

00:15:19.290 --> 00:15:22.090
the productivity
of organic farming.

00:15:22.090 --> 00:15:24.420
And we can use all
kinds of wastes

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:28.860
which are generated from
construction for creating that.

00:15:28.860 --> 00:15:31.270
So we also have an
animal farm, where

00:15:31.270 --> 00:15:34.020
we protect all these
different kinds of animals.

00:15:34.020 --> 00:15:37.670
And there's a whole free
range available for them to go

00:15:37.670 --> 00:15:39.050
and graze.

00:15:39.050 --> 00:15:42.360
And we have created very
huge, nice facilities for them

00:15:42.360 --> 00:15:45.240
to feel completely
protected and at ease.

00:15:45.240 --> 00:15:48.950
On a regular basis, every week,
all of the community members

00:15:48.950 --> 00:15:52.580
go and brush these
animals-- these cows

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:55.070
and other animals--
with brushes.

00:15:55.070 --> 00:15:58.220
And we have created such
a beautiful relationship

00:15:58.220 --> 00:16:02.650
with them that they
feel totally at ease

00:16:02.650 --> 00:16:06.000
and very, very friendly with
anyone who approaches them.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:10.990
And they also give
very nice milk.

00:16:10.990 --> 00:16:13.360
So then we have--
as far as food is

00:16:13.360 --> 00:16:16.160
concerned-- that is taken care.

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:19.300
Then as far as that
accommodation--

00:16:19.300 --> 00:16:21.850
compressed and
stabilized earth blocks.

00:16:21.850 --> 00:16:23.700
So these are some of
the guest rooms which

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:26.880
we have created with
the CSEB-- Compressed

00:16:26.880 --> 00:16:29.160
to Stabilized Earth Blocks.

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:34.530
So basically, it is
one portion of cement

00:16:34.530 --> 00:16:35.610
to six portion of sand.

00:16:35.610 --> 00:16:40.410
And the rest is all--
one cement, one mud,

00:16:40.410 --> 00:16:42.780
and four stone dust.

00:16:42.780 --> 00:16:44.580
The difference
between the energy

00:16:44.580 --> 00:16:48.510
consumed you can see--
72.3 megajoules per kg

00:16:48.510 --> 00:16:52.490
versus 0.275 megajoules per kg.

00:16:52.490 --> 00:16:54.400
A compressed to
stabilized earth block

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:56.760
has such low embodied energy.

00:16:56.760 --> 00:17:00.710
So you are saving such a major
amount of carbon footprint,

00:17:00.710 --> 00:17:05.829
just by deciding not to
utilize paint and plaster

00:17:05.829 --> 00:17:09.819
method for making walls.

00:17:09.819 --> 00:17:13.099
And thus, we find
that the energy we use

00:17:13.099 --> 00:17:16.500
is solar and
bio-gas for cooking.

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:18.119
These are some of
the solar panels.

00:17:18.119 --> 00:17:20.680
And what you see on the
right-hand bottom side

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:23.560
is what is known
as a bio-gas plant.

00:17:23.560 --> 00:17:25.250
You see the [INAUDIBLE] moving.

00:17:25.250 --> 00:17:30.500
So that is known as ADPM--
Animal Driven Prime Mover.

00:17:30.500 --> 00:17:32.590
So it is connected
to a gear system.

00:17:32.590 --> 00:17:35.060
And then it helps
pump the water out.

00:17:35.060 --> 00:17:39.870
And that water is utilized for
irrigating the fields nearby.

00:17:39.870 --> 00:17:44.320
And then, we have handling
of human waste, construction

00:17:44.320 --> 00:17:49.220
waste, and other construction
material inercity.

00:17:49.220 --> 00:17:53.550
And basically, recycling
the non-biodegradable wastes

00:17:53.550 --> 00:17:57.240
is done in various ways.

00:17:57.240 --> 00:18:00.490
We use it for waterproofing
of roof in construction.

00:18:00.490 --> 00:18:02.050
Because for
waterproofing, you need

00:18:02.050 --> 00:18:05.320
many of these bricks which are
broken and not in good shape.

00:18:05.320 --> 00:18:08.280
They are utilized for
waterproofing of the roof.

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:10.460
The dust which is generated
during construction

00:18:10.460 --> 00:18:15.480
is used for making agarbatti--
or incense sticks-- made out

00:18:15.480 --> 00:18:16.360
of cow dung.

00:18:16.360 --> 00:18:19.880
So it's a cow product-based
small scale industry.

00:18:19.880 --> 00:18:22.290
Then, as I showed in
the picture before,

00:18:22.290 --> 00:18:24.450
the bricks which are
broken down can also

00:18:24.450 --> 00:18:27.570
be used for making permanent
raised-bed technology.

00:18:27.570 --> 00:18:31.370
Then, many of these
leaves and grasses

00:18:31.370 --> 00:18:35.460
which are part of biodegradable
waste are used for mulching.

00:18:35.460 --> 00:18:38.910
Mulching is a technique by which
you cover the plants around

00:18:38.910 --> 00:18:40.810
so that they get some
kind of fertilizer.

00:18:40.810 --> 00:18:44.310
And at the same time, the
moisture which is there

00:18:44.310 --> 00:18:45.980
is retained.

00:18:45.980 --> 00:18:49.130
And the plastics
and others are also

00:18:49.130 --> 00:18:52.832
used as-- suppose cement
bags are generated.

00:18:52.832 --> 00:18:54.290
So if the cement
bags are there, we

00:18:54.290 --> 00:18:57.510
use them for composting
and plant bags.

00:18:57.510 --> 00:19:00.040
We are re-utilizing
them that way.

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:02.900
And some of the
other wastes we use

00:19:02.900 --> 00:19:05.920
in the walls for
which we make cob.

00:19:05.920 --> 00:19:09.400
So cob house is
actually mud house,

00:19:09.400 --> 00:19:11.110
but the walls can
actually be filled

00:19:11.110 --> 00:19:13.350
with various kinds
of wastes which

00:19:13.350 --> 00:19:16.400
are around-- say bottles or
tires or anything can be put

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:20.440
inside, and then covered
over and plastered with mud.

00:19:20.440 --> 00:19:23.130
So a lot of wastes
are also re-utilized

00:19:23.130 --> 00:19:25.670
in the walls of the cob house.

00:19:25.670 --> 00:19:28.320
So in this way, we
are trying to use

00:19:28.320 --> 00:19:32.930
the non-biodegradable
wastes in this fashion.

00:19:32.930 --> 00:19:38.220
Then we have the domestic waste
and the food and cattle waste.

00:19:38.220 --> 00:19:42.750
And other biodegradable waste,
all that is used in composting.

00:19:42.750 --> 00:19:44.720
Because it can be
composted, and it

00:19:44.720 --> 00:19:49.080
can be used as manure
for agriculture.

00:19:49.080 --> 00:19:53.450
So, the whole community,
it is very sensitive

00:19:53.450 --> 00:19:55.310
to separate all of these wastes.

00:19:55.310 --> 00:19:57.790
Because as you know,
the number one principle

00:19:57.790 --> 00:20:01.010
of waste management is
separation at source.

00:20:01.010 --> 00:20:02.740
And if we do not
separate at source,

00:20:02.740 --> 00:20:06.040
we cannot have a successful
waste management plan.

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:07.980
So therefore, this
composting unit

00:20:07.980 --> 00:20:10.590
is utilized in organic farming.

00:20:10.590 --> 00:20:14.000
So it is used in
bio-gas plant, and it

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:17.190
comes from cow barn, organic
farming, and community kitchen.

00:20:17.190 --> 00:20:21.150
These are the three sources of
giving us animal waste and food

00:20:21.150 --> 00:20:22.940
waste inputs.

00:20:22.940 --> 00:20:25.830
So all of these three go
into the bio-gas plant

00:20:25.830 --> 00:20:27.070
and give energy.

00:20:27.070 --> 00:20:29.160
The input is from these wastes.

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:33.610
The output is energy which
is utilized for cooking.

00:20:33.610 --> 00:20:35.310
So this is a picture of that.

00:20:37.850 --> 00:20:41.890
And then, we have
the last, which

00:20:41.890 --> 00:20:44.380
is the sewage-- or human waste.

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:48.220
And that is recycled in what is
known as the soil biotechnology

00:20:48.220 --> 00:20:49.400
plant.

00:20:49.400 --> 00:20:52.970
And the soil biotechnology
plant is actually

00:20:52.970 --> 00:20:56.230
an IET Mumbai patented plant.

00:20:56.230 --> 00:20:59.970
It is created by a Doctor
Biplab Patnaik, who

00:20:59.970 --> 00:21:02.680
was one of my classmates
from IET Mumbai.

00:21:02.680 --> 00:21:06.320
And I knew when he was doing
his PhD in '90, '93, '94,

00:21:06.320 --> 00:21:07.770
in that period.

00:21:07.770 --> 00:21:09.960
So Professor Shankar
and Dr. Biplab Patnaik

00:21:09.960 --> 00:21:11.970
created this technology.

00:21:11.970 --> 00:21:16.270
And the principle is very
simple-- water, by nature,

00:21:16.270 --> 00:21:16.770
regenerates.

00:21:19.620 --> 00:21:23.460
Even you don't drink
water for a few hours,

00:21:23.460 --> 00:21:26.270
you feel energy going down.

00:21:26.270 --> 00:21:29.880
So as soon as you start drinking
water, you generate energy.

00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:33.400
As soon as the plants get
water, they start generating.

00:21:33.400 --> 00:21:36.640
So water is a
regenerating medium.

00:21:36.640 --> 00:21:41.220
Whereas, the earth is best
for these degeneration,

00:21:41.220 --> 00:21:44.050
because the number of
bacteria which are in earth

00:21:44.050 --> 00:21:46.700
is several hundred times
more than the bacteria

00:21:46.700 --> 00:21:49.010
which is there in water.

00:21:49.010 --> 00:21:52.760
So therefore, the
degradation and degeneration

00:21:52.760 --> 00:21:55.260
happens more effectively,
more efficiently,

00:21:55.260 --> 00:21:59.050
naturally, in earth
than in water.

00:21:59.050 --> 00:22:02.250
So previously, all
of the wastes would

00:22:02.250 --> 00:22:04.680
be actually dumped
in the outside.

00:22:04.680 --> 00:22:06.980
And people would
in the out and then

00:22:06.980 --> 00:22:09.340
they would respond to
the call of nature.

00:22:09.340 --> 00:22:12.390
Then we had this
flush-driven toilet system.

00:22:12.390 --> 00:22:14.880
So because of the
flush-driven toilet system,

00:22:14.880 --> 00:22:17.700
we had water as the
medium for transporting

00:22:17.700 --> 00:22:20.080
all of the gray and black water.

00:22:20.080 --> 00:22:23.450
So as a result, what do you
do with all of that waste?

00:22:23.450 --> 00:22:28.490
So the statistics reveal that
very few municipalities all

00:22:28.490 --> 00:22:31.910
over the world-- city
councils all over the world--

00:22:31.910 --> 00:22:35.220
take the trouble of actually
processing that waste

00:22:35.220 --> 00:22:37.280
before they dump
it into the ocean.

00:22:37.280 --> 00:22:39.100
So the majority of
the times, it just

00:22:39.100 --> 00:22:43.630
goes, because the cost of
handling that is enormous.

00:22:43.630 --> 00:22:48.280
So the thought
behind SBD was that,

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:51.980
since you cannot now tell
people to go out-- you know,

00:22:51.980 --> 00:22:55.640
they have to use the toilet,
so as far as water-based,

00:22:55.640 --> 00:22:57.920
gravity-driven sewage
system is concerned,

00:22:57.920 --> 00:22:59.964
that cannot be replaced.

00:22:59.964 --> 00:23:02.380
But what if that water which
is brought through the sewage

00:23:02.380 --> 00:23:06.440
system can finally be
processed through a soil-based,

00:23:06.440 --> 00:23:09.320
earth-based,
purification system?

00:23:09.320 --> 00:23:13.330
So it is combining
the ancient wisdom

00:23:13.330 --> 00:23:18.100
of using earth as a purifying
medium with the modern usage

00:23:18.100 --> 00:23:20.400
of the flush toilet system.

00:23:20.400 --> 00:23:24.810
So then we have what is
known as SBD bio-reactor.

00:23:24.810 --> 00:23:27.520
It goes into the SBD
system-- the human waste.

00:23:27.520 --> 00:23:29.950
And output which comes
out is fish-fit water

00:23:29.950 --> 00:23:33.320
which is used for
nursery and landscaping.

00:23:33.320 --> 00:23:40.380
OK, so basically, the SBD
is very powerful system.

00:23:40.380 --> 00:23:40.880
Why?

00:23:40.880 --> 00:23:43.550
Because septic tank-based
system is-- many times,

00:23:43.550 --> 00:23:47.340
it creates foul
odor and it clogs,

00:23:47.340 --> 00:23:49.300
and then it spills
over and creates

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:53.270
lot of difficulties in
rural areas especially.

00:23:53.270 --> 00:23:56.520
So here, when we have
an SBD-based system--

00:23:56.520 --> 00:23:59.060
so we have at least 10
million liter of water

00:23:59.060 --> 00:24:00.960
to be used for irrigation.

00:24:00.960 --> 00:24:04.110
Number two, the
solid waste-- it also

00:24:04.110 --> 00:24:07.590
creates photosynthetic biomass
for internal use, which

00:24:07.590 --> 00:24:09.590
is like manure.

00:24:09.590 --> 00:24:14.040
So basically, this is how
a schematic looks like.

00:24:14.040 --> 00:24:17.400
This is the stage one
of the SBD system,

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:21.800
where from the last manhole,
then the pipe comes in,

00:24:21.800 --> 00:24:24.470
then you see those two
perforated screens-- that

00:24:24.470 --> 00:24:26.990
separates the solid
waste from the liquid--

00:24:26.990 --> 00:24:30.270
and then the liquid comes
in, goes on a settling tank,

00:24:30.270 --> 00:24:32.570
and the overflow goes
into the next tank, which

00:24:32.570 --> 00:24:34.580
is called the collection tank.

00:24:34.580 --> 00:24:38.440
From the collection tank
through a transfer pump,

00:24:38.440 --> 00:24:40.800
it is fed in through
the feed lines

00:24:40.800 --> 00:24:44.310
into the SBD bio-reactive unit.

00:24:44.310 --> 00:24:47.800
So you see those rocks,
they appear as hard rocks.

00:24:47.800 --> 00:24:49.790
But they're not hard rocks.

00:24:49.790 --> 00:24:54.010
When you have a lot of
mud which is hardened

00:24:54.010 --> 00:24:56.650
over a period of
time, naturally, then

00:24:56.650 --> 00:25:00.640
has as a fantastic
phenomenon of being hard,

00:25:00.640 --> 00:25:03.660
but at the same
time it is porous.

00:25:03.660 --> 00:25:06.800
It is porous because it allows
the water to flow through.

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:08.950
At the same time, even
if water flows through,

00:25:08.950 --> 00:25:11.860
it will not disintegrate
like regular mud.

00:25:11.860 --> 00:25:13.910
It will not flow with the mud.

00:25:13.910 --> 00:25:16.250
So that is one of the
secrets of this plant.

00:25:16.250 --> 00:25:19.410
And along with that, you
add geophagus earthworms

00:25:19.410 --> 00:25:25.329
who have a natural tendency
off purifying and converting.

00:25:25.329 --> 00:25:27.370
So then, along with that,
you have specific kinds

00:25:27.370 --> 00:25:30.450
of plants which
you grow in that.

00:25:30.450 --> 00:25:34.230
And when you do that, what comes
out is this fish-fit water.

00:25:34.230 --> 00:25:36.400
And this is how the
SBD unit looks like.

00:25:36.400 --> 00:25:37.900
If you look at it
from outside, this

00:25:37.900 --> 00:25:40.120
is a sewage treatment plant.

00:25:40.120 --> 00:25:42.330
It looks like a garden.

00:25:42.330 --> 00:25:45.140
These are the papayas
which are grown there.

00:25:45.140 --> 00:25:47.380
And you know, there is a
whole discussion going on

00:25:47.380 --> 00:25:50.620
that these papayas look
bigger than the normal.

00:25:50.620 --> 00:25:53.500
They're well fed--
powerful looking.

00:25:53.500 --> 00:25:55.140
And you'll see in
the bottle, it's

00:25:55.140 --> 00:25:57.790
the purified water which
is completely clear.

00:25:57.790 --> 00:26:00.180
So impact assessment,
if you see,

00:26:00.180 --> 00:26:05.480
that as far as treatment is
concerned-- sludge handling is

00:26:05.480 --> 00:26:07.450
concerned, aeration
is concerned--

00:26:07.450 --> 00:26:10.090
is SBD-- the soil
biotechnologies-- scores

00:26:10.090 --> 00:26:13.030
over the conventional
unit hands down.

00:26:13.030 --> 00:26:13.770
Why?

00:26:13.770 --> 00:26:17.930
Because practically no chemical
is required for treatment.

00:26:17.930 --> 00:26:19.820
Sludge handling
hardly is required,

00:26:19.820 --> 00:26:23.540
because we have around two
and a half kilometers--

00:26:23.540 --> 00:26:26.790
yeah, two kilometers
of line which come in.

00:26:26.790 --> 00:26:29.410
And by the time it
comes in, the water

00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:32.570
has already kind of taken care
of all of the solid wasted.

00:26:32.570 --> 00:26:35.010
So comes out is like
a liquid slurry.

00:26:35.010 --> 00:26:37.470
So sludge handling
is hardly there.

00:26:37.470 --> 00:26:39.680
And thirdly, as far as
aeration is concerned,

00:26:39.680 --> 00:26:41.730
there is no requirement
for aeration,

00:26:41.730 --> 00:26:44.810
because it's a simple,
gravity-driven,

00:26:44.810 --> 00:26:47.880
you know, earth-based,
rock-based system.

00:26:47.880 --> 00:26:49.370
So there's no need for aeration.

00:26:49.370 --> 00:26:51.140
So there's no need for
high mechanization.

00:26:51.140 --> 00:26:54.080
There's no downtime required.

00:26:54.080 --> 00:26:55.930
There is no sound
created, so it can

00:26:55.930 --> 00:26:59.640
be installed very close
to human dwellings.

00:26:59.640 --> 00:27:05.540
Because conventional septic
tanks and conventional units

00:27:05.540 --> 00:27:07.520
for STPs-- sewage
treatment plants--

00:27:07.520 --> 00:27:09.550
cannot be installed very
near where people stay

00:27:09.550 --> 00:27:13.810
because of the sound it
creates for the aeration unit.

00:27:13.810 --> 00:27:17.910
And so we can see such a low
energy expended for one liter

00:27:17.910 --> 00:27:22.401
sewage is less than
0.01 kilowatt hour.

00:27:22.401 --> 00:27:23.900
So these are some
of the advantages.

00:27:23.900 --> 00:27:27.510
It's sustainable, ease
of installation, recovery

00:27:27.510 --> 00:27:32.480
efficiency-- we practically
recover 95% of the water--

00:27:32.480 --> 00:27:34.910
and we are, as I said, 10
million liters of freshwater

00:27:34.910 --> 00:27:36.830
we are generating.

00:27:36.830 --> 00:27:38.540
And it's power saving.

00:27:38.540 --> 00:27:43.610
And also, we have this biomass
flowers, bio-fertilizers,

00:27:43.610 --> 00:27:46.750
and we have a whole garden
which is created around that.

00:27:46.750 --> 00:27:50.990
So flowers and fruits are
generated also along with that.

00:27:50.990 --> 00:27:57.880
The BOD, the COD, the
units-- if you compare,

00:27:57.880 --> 00:28:01.530
it's very, very low,
you can see that.

00:28:01.530 --> 00:28:04.960
The standard specification
is maximum 250.

00:28:04.960 --> 00:28:07.620
So in December, 2012 and Jan.

00:28:07.620 --> 00:28:11.170
2013 when we began, we
have some of these figures.

00:28:11.170 --> 00:28:15.510
So you can see the treated
water is 42 and 38.

00:28:15.510 --> 00:28:16.010
Right?

00:28:16.010 --> 00:28:20.390
Chemically oxidized,
and then BOD.

00:28:20.390 --> 00:28:25.010
So biological also--
it's 18 and16,

00:28:25.010 --> 00:28:28.440
which is much less than
the standard specification.

00:28:28.440 --> 00:28:31.600
Suspended solids are very
less, and total dissolved

00:28:31.600 --> 00:28:35.240
solids which also came
out to be extremely low.

00:28:35.240 --> 00:28:40.630
Standard specification is
2,100, here we had 402.

00:28:40.630 --> 00:28:44.970
So overall, we have found
that this symbiotic recycling

00:28:44.970 --> 00:28:46.690
has turned out to be great.

00:28:46.690 --> 00:28:50.010
As far as cost is concerned,
we are recovering the cost,

00:28:50.010 --> 00:28:52.230
and we are saving
a lot on energy.

00:28:52.230 --> 00:28:55.420
We are saving on the
monthly cost a net savings.

00:28:55.420 --> 00:28:59.040
And in this way, we can see
that the value created by SBD

00:28:59.040 --> 00:29:01.700
is also tremendous,
because it saves us

00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:04.970
around 35,000 rupees per annum
on the water being generated

00:29:04.970 --> 00:29:07.200
and 2 million tons of biomass.

00:29:07.200 --> 00:29:09.400
And what to speak of
the co-products which

00:29:09.400 --> 00:29:11.927
are produced as a result of
the waste created from the cow

00:29:11.927 --> 00:29:13.460
dung?

00:29:13.460 --> 00:29:17.510
And this is a 10
million liter pond.

00:29:17.510 --> 00:29:20.470
You see the mountains behind
are called the Sahyadri Mountain

00:29:20.470 --> 00:29:21.360
Ranges.

00:29:21.360 --> 00:29:25.560
It's one of the top biodiversity
hotspots in the world.

00:29:25.560 --> 00:29:28.970
The monsoons hit against that,
now it's lashing like anything.

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:32.970
July to September, you'll get
3,000 millimeters of rain.

00:29:32.970 --> 00:29:35.700
London gets around 500 to 600.

00:29:35.700 --> 00:29:38.330
So in this three to four
months, the amount of rain

00:29:38.330 --> 00:29:41.000
which falls-- so we
need to conserve that.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:44.000
Because as you know, India's
population is 1.2 billion,

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:47.520
out of which 820 million
live in villages.

00:29:47.520 --> 00:29:51.070
And villages very
much live upon water.

00:29:51.070 --> 00:29:53.750
So therefore, if we
create a model by which we

00:29:53.750 --> 00:29:56.890
show an ideal example
of water conservation,

00:29:56.890 --> 00:29:59.340
it can transform the
landscape of the country.

00:29:59.340 --> 00:30:01.600
So the step one in doing
this water consideration

00:30:01.600 --> 00:30:05.170
is what is known as
hydrogeological survey.

00:30:05.170 --> 00:30:07.630
So there is a firm
called ACWADAM in Pune,

00:30:07.630 --> 00:30:08.970
and we employed them.

00:30:08.970 --> 00:30:11.420
And they did a complete
hydrogeological survey,

00:30:11.420 --> 00:30:16.210
which means they showed the
movement of the ground water

00:30:16.210 --> 00:30:17.840
under your property.

00:30:17.840 --> 00:30:20.460
And they showed the potential
moment of the rainwater

00:30:20.460 --> 00:30:24.640
once the rain hits, depending
on the topography of the land.

00:30:24.640 --> 00:30:27.760
So it costs a little
bit to do this survey,

00:30:27.760 --> 00:30:32.220
but once you do that, you have a
very accurate estimate of where

00:30:32.220 --> 00:30:34.280
you must try to
conserve the rainwater,

00:30:34.280 --> 00:30:36.780
and where you should
dig the wells.

00:30:36.780 --> 00:30:39.270
And this water conservation
is closely connected

00:30:39.270 --> 00:30:40.940
to organic farming.

00:30:40.940 --> 00:30:41.770
Why?

00:30:41.770 --> 00:30:44.880
Because one of the major
culprits for groundwater

00:30:44.880 --> 00:30:48.920
contamination is fertilizers
and insecticides.

00:30:48.920 --> 00:30:51.470
And when the rains
fall, then the rains

00:30:51.470 --> 00:30:53.350
percolate down into
the groundwater

00:30:53.350 --> 00:30:55.420
and pollute the aquifers.

00:30:55.420 --> 00:30:58.010
And when the overflow
comes through,

00:30:58.010 --> 00:31:01.090
it pollutes all the
rivers and the ponds.

00:31:01.090 --> 00:31:04.330
All of this rainwater
carries the insecticides

00:31:04.330 --> 00:31:06.500
and the pesticides with them.

00:31:06.500 --> 00:31:09.720
So if we think that we can
separate water conservation

00:31:09.720 --> 00:31:12.050
from farming, it
is not possible.

00:31:12.050 --> 00:31:14.880
Because what we
use as fertilizers,

00:31:14.880 --> 00:31:17.910
pesticides, and insecticides
in our organic farming

00:31:17.910 --> 00:31:20.520
will ultimately come
back in the form

00:31:20.520 --> 00:31:23.330
of contaminated groundwater.

00:31:23.330 --> 00:31:27.960
So therefore, we partnered with
the government of Maharashtra.

00:31:27.960 --> 00:31:31.480
And we had a geo-membrane
laid in this particular patch

00:31:31.480 --> 00:31:32.610
of land.

00:31:32.610 --> 00:31:34.850
And according to the
hydrogeological survey,

00:31:34.850 --> 00:31:38.320
this place was shown to be the
best for conserving the water.

00:31:38.320 --> 00:31:40.480
So the water hits against
the mountains, flows down

00:31:40.480 --> 00:31:44.480
the mountains, and this
10 million liters water

00:31:44.480 --> 00:31:47.850
is filled up in three
day of rainfall.

00:31:47.850 --> 00:31:50.314
In three days of rainfall,
it is full and overflowing.

00:31:50.314 --> 00:31:51.730
And then we have
created a channel

00:31:51.730 --> 00:31:54.020
through which it goes farther.

00:31:54.020 --> 00:31:58.570
And then, we have
created-- this is actually

00:31:58.570 --> 00:32:02.040
what you call as a
rainwater harvesting unit.

00:32:02.040 --> 00:32:03.700
Then you have
another unit-- which

00:32:03.700 --> 00:32:06.130
is called percolation
tank-- by which

00:32:06.130 --> 00:32:09.010
we allow the rainwater
to go through the earth,

00:32:09.010 --> 00:32:12.460
down, and regenerate
the aquifers.

00:32:12.460 --> 00:32:16.970
So all of the extra water from
here goes into the other pond.

00:32:16.970 --> 00:32:20.370
And then, that pond
actually percolates down.

00:32:20.370 --> 00:32:22.650
And overall, in the
last four years,

00:32:22.650 --> 00:32:25.950
we have seen that our
groundwater levels have come up

00:32:25.950 --> 00:32:31.240
by three feet because of
continuous percolation.

00:32:31.240 --> 00:32:34.030
So in this way, we can see
that the linear systems prove

00:32:34.030 --> 00:32:36.430
to be injurious,
costlier and inadequate.

00:32:36.430 --> 00:32:38.890
Symbiotic systems
are more efficient.

00:32:38.890 --> 00:32:42.790
And these systems which
are implemented in GEV

00:32:42.790 --> 00:32:44.710
can be scaled up.

00:32:44.710 --> 00:32:46.429
And we already in
dialogue with FICI--

00:32:46.429 --> 00:32:48.470
which is Federation of
Indian Chamber of Commerce

00:32:48.470 --> 00:32:53.270
and Industry-- and CII--
Chamber of Indian Industries--

00:32:53.270 --> 00:32:55.800
and also the government
of Maharashtra.

00:32:55.800 --> 00:32:59.040
And we are trying ways and means
by which this can be scaled up,

00:32:59.040 --> 00:33:02.540
and the example can be utilized
in various other places.

00:33:02.540 --> 00:33:04.940
We have tried it
to great success,

00:33:04.940 --> 00:33:08.390
and it is up to the government
and the corporate agencies

00:33:08.390 --> 00:33:11.300
to utilize the
resources to scale it up

00:33:11.300 --> 00:33:12.750
for the help of society.

00:33:12.750 --> 00:33:16.110
An SBD is definitely a quite
green and more effective

00:33:16.110 --> 00:33:17.694
than any other system.

00:33:17.694 --> 00:33:19.610
So these are some of the
thoughts on Govardhan

00:33:19.610 --> 00:33:21.400
Ecovillage Symbiotic Recycling.

